<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-20T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-20T09:00:00-05:00" n="271" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d271">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 657.119/374</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schmedeman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Christiania</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-20T15:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">March 20, 1918—3 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5.07 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>600. Minister of Foreign Affairs informed me yesterday that Norwegian
                                Government was negotiating with Germany in regard to commodity
                                exchange. He said that Germany was asking for a written statement of
                                commodities to be sent to Germany. In reply to a question as to what
                                compensation was expected His Excellency told me it was wrought and
                                pig iron, steel plates, and medicines. I have no information about
                                exact quantities.</p>
                            <p>With regard to the American agreement, Minister for Foreign Affairs
                                expressed the hope that it would be signed by April 1 and seemed
                                pleased at the prospect. Meanwhile general opinion is somewhat
                                depressed and pessimistic regarding outcome of negotiations with us
                                and it is not improbable that the Government plans to make use of
                                this feeling for political purposes as soon as the agreement is
                                concluded.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schmedeman</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>